#if-else statements

#What if in your if statement you want to have it execute one action when it passes but also executes something
#when it does not pass?

#if-else statements are there for when there are 2 different outcomes when seeing if conditions are met.
#the else statement is for when the condition does NOT pass.

#Here is an example:

age = 17 #Here our age is under the requirement to vote, which means this condition will not pass.
if age >= 18:
  print("You are old enough to vote!")
  print("Have you registered to vote yet?")
else: #here is the else statement and since the condition will not pass, we will see this block of code execute.
  print("Sorry you are too young to vote.")
  print("Please register to vote as soon as you turn 18!")


  #if-else statements work when you want 2 different outcomes in your python code.

#if-else chain

#There will be times when you need to test more than 2 possible situations and this is where if-else chains
#comes in.

#It runs each conditional test in order until one passes, when the test passes the following code skips the
#rest of the tests.

#For example, say you want to see the price rate for an anmusement park based on different age groups
#Here is an example:

#Admission is free for anyone under 4 years old
#Admission for anyone between the ages of 4 and 18 is $5
#Admission for anyone age 18 or older is $10

age = 12

if age < 4:
  print("Your admission cost is $0.")
elif age < 18:
  print("Your admission is $5")
else:
  print("Your admission is $10")

#Instead of printing the admission price inside the if-elif-else block, you can
#set the price inside the if-elif-else chain and have a simple print statement when the tests runs

age = 12

if age < 4:
  price = 0 #We set the value of the prices here
elif age < 18:
  price = 5 #We set the value of the prices here
else:
  price = 10 #We set the value of the prices here
print("Your admissions cost is $"+str(price)+".")

#The whole purpose of this exmaple was to show the chain more narrower so it can determine the admission price
#And also you can modify it more easily just by changing one print statement instead of 3.

#Using multiple elif blocks
#Lets say for our admission example we want to add a price for senior citizens
age = 12

if age < 4:
  price = 0
elif age < 18:
  price = 5
elif age > 65:
  price = 10
else:
  price = 5

print("Your admissions cost is $"+str(price)+".")

